We recommended the following courses of action:

1. Submit  written  explanation  to  justify  the  occurrence  of  the  said transactions;

2. Prepare and submit regularly  the  required  monthly  reports  using  the format as prescribed in the Manual  on  Audit  for  Fuel  Consumption  of Government Motor Vehicles;
3. Properly accomplish the prescribed Driver’s Trip Tickets on travels  made using government motor vehicles;
4. Cause the repair of the ODOMETER of government vehicle  if  this  is  not functioning, otherwise all purchases of gasoline, oil and lubricants will be disallowed in audit; and
5. Enjoin compliance with COA Circular  No.  77-61  dated  September  26  to avoid disallowance in audit due to irregularity of transactions  or  non- compliance of existing  laws,  rules  and  regulations  on  gasoline/fuel consumption.

We  recommended  that  the Local Chief Executive strictly monitor the recently issued  Executive  Order to:
   a. Conduct completely the annual physical  count  of  all  the  property,  plant and  equipment  owned  by  the  Municipality  to  establish  the  existence and correct the balances of PPE accounts;
   b. Prepare promptly the Report on the Physical Count of PPE;
   c. Submit religiously the RPCPPE to the Auditor concerned not later  than January 31 of each year;
   d. Create an Appraisal Committee to appraise all  properties  whose  cost  cannot  be reliably  determined  due  to  unavailability  of  financial records. Require the committee to prepare Appraisal Report and  submit  it  to  Commission  on  Audit  for  Technical  Review  and Inspection.

      We also recommended that the  OIC-GSO  and  the  Municipal  Accountant shall  completely  maintain  the  prescribed  Property   Cards   and   PPELC respectively and reconcile it with  the  RPCPPE  to  establish  the  correct amount of the PPE in the financial statements.
      It is also noteworthy  that  accomplishing  these  recommendations  is vital and significantly important as these would make the PPE  accounts  and the  Financial  Statements  as  a  whole,  reliable,  accurate  and   fairly presented.
